<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>

<section xml:id="notes-week-01">
  <title>Week 1</title>

  <subsection>
    <title>Monday</title>

    <p>
In many problems we can bypass a
<m>
    u
</m>
-substitution if we know that the antiderivative involves a particular function. For example, in the integration problem
<m>
    \int e^{3x}\ dx
</m>
we know that the antiderivative involves
<m>
    e^{3x}
</m>
since the derivative of
<m>
    e^{3x}
</m>
is
<m>
    3 e^{3x}.
</m>
We could use a
<m>
    u
</m>
-substitution with
<m>
    u=3x,
</m>
however it's much easier to observe that the antiderivative involves
<m>
    e^{3x}
</m>
and then we can multiply or divide by a constant to arrive at the correct antiderivative.
    </p>
  </subsection>


  <dl>
      <li>
          <title/>
          <p>
              <alert>Problem I:</alert> Integrate by inspection.
          </p>

          <p>
              <dl>
                  <li>
                      <title>(a)</title>

                      <p>
                          <m>\displaystyle \int e^{4x}\ dx</m>
                      </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                      <title>(b)</title>

                      <p>
                          <m>\displaystyle \int e^{-x/2}\ dx</m>
                      </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                      <title>(c)</title>

                      <p>
                          <m>\displaystyle \int \sec^{2} (3x) \ dx</m>
                      </p>

                      <p/>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                      <title>(d)</title>

                      <p>
                          <m>\displaystyle \int \sin \pi x \ dx</m>
                      </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                      <title>(e)</title>

                      <p>
                          <m>\displaystyle \int \cos \frac{\theta}{2}\ d \theta</m>
                      </p>
                  </li>
              </dl>
          </p>
      </li>

      <li>
          <title/>
          <p>
              <alert>Try it on your own!</alert>
          </p>

          <p>
              <dl>
                  <li>
                      <title>(a)</title>

                      <p>
                          <m>\displaystyle \int e^{-9x}\ dx</m>
                      </p>
                  </li>

                  <li>
                      <title>(b)</title>

                      <p>
                          <m>\displaystyle \int \cos 3x \ dx</m>
                      </p>
                  </li>
              </dl>
          </p>
      </li>
  </dl>
